  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in Milan with parents who both have bachelor's degrees, I was always encouraged to pursue education, but I never quite felt the same level of confidence in math and science as I did in my carpentry work. As a carpenter, I know that hands-on skills are what matter most, but in STEM fields, the pressure to conform to stereotypes about who belongs there can be incredibly real. I've noticed that when people from underrepresented groups—like women or people from certain cultural backgrounds—enter STEM environments, they often feel like they're being judged not on their abilities but on their perceived fit within a system that's already stacked against them. This isn't just about individual performance; it's about systemic issues that can deter talent from entering the field altogether. From what I've seen, addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it needs concrete action. For example, creating mentorship programs that pair students with role models who share similar backgrounds can help build confidence. Also, fostering inclusive classrooms where everyone feels valued, not just the 'typical' STEM students, is crucial. I've seen this work in my community through local workshops where people from diverse backgrounds learn practical skills together, and it's made a real difference. The key is to make sure that the solutions are tailored to the specific needs of the community and not just applied in a one-size-fits-all way. Ultimately, if we want to have a more diverse and innovative STEM workforce, we need to tackle stereotype threat head-on, not just as a side issue but as a core part of how we build the future.",
